2 SENATE BILL 792
1 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
2 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
3 Article – Health – General
4 19–201.
5 (a) In this subtitle the following words have the meanings indicated.
6 (c) “Commission” means the State Health Services Cost Review Commission.
7 19–207.
8 (a) In addition to the powers set forth elsewhere in this subtitle, the Commission
9 may:
10 (1) Adopt rules and regulations to carry out the provisions of this subtitle;
11 (2) Create committees from among its members;
12 (3) Appoint advisory committees, which may include individuals and
13 representatives of interested public or private organizations;
14 (4) Apply for and accept any funds, property, or services from any person
15 or government agency;
16 (5) Make agreements with a grantor or payor of funds, property, or
17 services, including an agreement to make any study, plan, demonstration, or project;
18 (6) Publish and give out any information that relates to the financial
19 aspects of health care and is considered desirable in the public interest; and
20 (7) Subject to the limitations of this subtitle, exercise any other power that
21 is reasonably necessary to carry out the purposes of this subtitle.
22 (b) In addition to the duties set forth elsewhere in this subtitle, the Commission
23 shall:
24 (1) Adopt rules and regulations that relate to its meetings, minutes, and
25 transactions;
26 (2) Keep minutes of each meeting;
27 (3) Prepare annually a budget proposal that includes the estimated income
28 of the Commission and proposed expenses for its administration and operation;

SENATE BILL 792 3
1 (4) Within a reasonable time after the end of each facility’s fiscal year or
2 more often as the Commission determines, prepare from the information filed with the
3 Commission any summary, compilation, or other supplementary report that will advance
4 the purposes of this subtitle;
5 (5) Periodically participate in or do analyses and studies that relate to:
6 (i) Health care costs;
7 (ii) The financial status of any facility; or
8 (iii) Any other appropriate matter;
9 (6) On or before May 1 of each year, submit to the Governor, to the
10 Secretary, and, subject to § 2–1257 of the State Government Article, to the General
11 Assembly an annual report on the operations and activities of the Commission during the
12 preceding fiscal year, including:
13 (i) A copy of each summary, compilation, and supplementary report
14 required by this subtitle;
15 (ii) Budget information regarding the Health Services Cost Review
16 Commission Fund, including:
17 1. Any balance remaining in the Fund at the end of the
18 previous fiscal year; and
19 2. The percentage of the total annual costs of the
20 Commission that is represented by the balance remaining in the Fund at the end of the
21 previous fiscal year;
22 (iii) A summary of the Commission’s role in hospital quality of care
23 activities, including information about the status of any pay for performance initiatives;
24 (iv) An update on the status of the State’s compliance with the
25 provisions of the all–payer model contract that includes:
26 1. Performance in limiting inpatient and outpatient hospital
27 per capita cost growth for all payers;
28 2. Annual progress toward achieving the State’s financial
29 targets established by the all–payer model contract;
30 3. A summary of the work conducted, recommendations
31 made, including recommendations made by workgroups created to provide technical input
32 and advice, and Commission action on activities related to the all–payer model contract;

4 SENATE BILL 792
1 4. Actions approved by the Commission to promote
2 alternative methods of rate determination and payment of an experimental nature, as
3 authorized under § 19–219(c)(2) of this subtitle;
4 5. Reports submitted to the federal Center for Medicare and
5 Medicaid Innovation relating to the all–payer model contract;
6 6. Any known adverse consequences in implementing the
7 all–payer model contract, as reported to the federal Center for Medicare and Medicaid
8 Innovation, that may negatively impact quality of or access to care, and the actions taken
9 by the Commission to mitigate the consequences; and
10 7. Annual progress made in the development of public and
11 private partnerships between hospitals and other entities, including community–based
12 physicians, community–based organizations, and other post–acute care providers, to
13 achieve the population health goals established with the federal Center for Medicare and
14 Medicaid Innovation; and
15 (v) Any other fact, suggestion, or policy recommendation that the
16 Commission considers necessary;
17 (7) Oversee and administer the Maryland Trauma Physician Services
18 Fund in conjunction with the Maryland Health Care Commission; [and]
19 (8) If the Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services issues a warning
20 notice related to a “triggering event” as described in the all–payer model contract, provide
21 written notification to the Governor, the Secretary, and, subject to § 2–1257 of the State
22 Government Article, the General Assembly within 15 days after the issuance of the notice;
23 (9) IN CONSULTATION WITH THE ATTORNEY GENERAL AND THE
24 MARYLAND HOSPITAL ASSOCIATION, DEVELOP A MODEL POLICY FOR HOSPITALS IN
25 THE STATE ADDRESSING HOW A HOSPITAL SHALL RESPOND TO IMMIGRATION
26 ENFORCEMENT ACTIONS AT THE HOSPITAL, WITH CONSIDERATION OF PATIENT
27 PRIVACY AND THE SAFETY OF PATIENTS, GUESTS, AND STAFF; AND
28 (10) ON OR BEFORE OCTOBER 1, 2026, PUBLISH THE MODEL POLICY
29 DEVELOPED UNDER ITEM (9) OF THIS SUBSECTION ON ITS WEBSITE.
30 19–306.
31 (A) (1) THE REQUIREMENTS OF THIS SUBSECTION DO NOT APPLY TO A
32 HOSPITAL OPERATED BY A UNIT OF STATE OR LOCAL GOVERNMENT REQUIRED TO
33 IMPLEMENT A POLICY CONSISTENT WITH THE GUIDANCE OF THE ATTORNEY
34 GENERAL UNDER § 6–111 OF THE STATE GOVERNMENT ARTICLE.

SENATE BILL 792 5
1 (2) A HOSPITAL SHALL ADOPT:
2 (1) ADOPT A POLICY DESCRIBING THE PROTOCOL OF THE HOSPITAL
3 WHEN THERE IS AN IMMIGRATION ENFORCEMENT ACTION AT THE HOSPITAL ON OR
4 BEFORE THE EARLIER OF:
5 (I) JANUARY 1, 2027; OR
6 (II) 3 MONTHS AFTER THE COMMISSION PUBLISHES A MODEL
7 POLICY UNDER § 19–207(B)(10) OF THIS TITLE. CONSISTENT WITH THE GUIDANCE
8 OF THE ATTORNEY GENERAL ISSUED UNDER § 6–111 OF THE STATE GOVERNMENT
9 ARTICLE;
10 (B) A HOSPITAL SHALL:
11 (1) (2) CONSPICUOUSLY POST COPIES OF MAKE THE HOSPITAL’S
12 IMMIGRATION ENFORCEMENT ACTION POLICY ON THE HOSPITAL’S WEBSITE
13 AVAILABLE TO ALL HOSPITAL STAFF MEMBERS; AND
14 (2) (3) PROVIDE ANNUAL TRAINING TO ALL HOSPITAL STAFF
15 MEMBERS TO ENSURE THE STAFF’S KNOWLEDGE AND UNDERSTANDING OF THE
16 IMMIGRATION ENFORCEMENT ACTION POLICY.
17 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect June
18 1, 2026.
